description:
Trigger: BIP-39 allows repeated words (e.g. 'zoo zoo zoo ... vote' is a valid 24-word mnemonic). The display loop uses words.iter().position(|w| w == &row[0]) which always returns the index of the FIRST occurrence of row[0] in the full word list. For a mnemonic where 'zoo' appears in positions 0-22, every chunk after the first will compute start=1 instead of 5, 9, 13, 17, 21. The user writes down labels '1. zoo 2. zoo 3. zoo 4. zoo' for EVERY row except the last.

Bad behavior: user writes down word numbers based on display, attempts to restore from backup in a different wallet using those numbers as reference, discovers words are correctly ordered but incorrectly labeled. Does not corrupt the wallet itself, but creates a mislabeled backup that could cause confusion during restore.

Fix: replace iter().position() with chunks(4).enumerate():
  for (chunk_idx, row) in words.chunks(4).enumerate() {
      let start = chunk_idx * 4 + 1;
      for (j, word) in row.iter().enumerate() {
          print!("{:2}. {:<12}", start + j, word);
      }
      println!();
  }
